				<td rowspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" style="text-align: justify;" width="100%" valign=top>
				<div></div><div>(1) I said coarse silk swatches, not coarse silk.  Yes, it takes 2 coarse silks to make 1 coarse silk swatch.</div><div>(2) My numbers were slightly wrong in 2 areas: (a) I ignored the effect of Salvage 3 and (b) I ignored the fact that plate had one extra subcombine (which presumably had a 95% success rate cap on it).  I also didn't provide any figures for the augments (which require no subcombine involving the MDS/GDH).</div><div> </div><div>I went back and assumed that salvage 3 meant a 25% chance to retrieve each piece of the combine.  The results were as follows:</div><div> </div><div>Slot                Expected MDS/GDH (chain/leather)          Expected MDS used (plate)                 MDS/GDH used for aug</div><div>Wrist                         1.13                                                         1.17                                                      1.08</div><div>Glove                         1.23                                                         1.28                                                      1.19</div><div>Sleeve                       1.37                                                         1.42                                                      1.32</div><div>Boots/Helm                2.47                                                         2.56                                                      1.19</div><div>Legs/BP                     4.68                                                         4.79                                                      1.50</div><div> </div><div>Set total                  19.15                                                      19.74                                                     10.05</div><div> </div><div>Whether coarse silk is more like plate or more like chain/leather depends on whether the combine from coarse silk to coarse silk swatches is no fail.  If it is no fail, take the chain/leather column and multiply by two for the expected number of coarse silks used.  If there is a risk of failure, take the plate column and multiply by two for the expected number of coarse silks used.  Coarse silk swatches cannot be used to make GM augments to the best of my knowledge ... and given their relative scarsity, who would want to anyway?  For those folks interested in making full sets of GM cultural armor, this does indicate that you should start by gathering approximately 30 MDS/GDH ... (i.e. expect failures to eat 8 which are not saved by salvage).</div><div> </div><div>Hope this calculation is useful ... details available on request.</div>
				
				</td></tr>
